<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="168" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,1204,2092]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FF2FFB3BEA46FB72" box="[189,272,1204,1228]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="Though" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Though</location>
most recorded specimens are from 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FD3CFB3BE9A3FB72" box="[686,757,1204,1228]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="Africa" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Africa</location>
, there are scattered occurrences throughout tropical 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FADAFB3BEE2FFB72" box="[1352,1401,1204,1228]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="Asia" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Asia</location>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[136,237,1240,1264]" name="Australia" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Australia</collectingCountry>
. 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FF6AFB57EA58FB51" box="[248,270,1240,1263]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="In" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">In</location>
the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FEAEFB57EAF3FB4E" box="[316,421,1240,1264]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="Americas" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Americas</location>
, it is known mainly from 
<collectingCountry box="[700,768,1240,1264]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and several 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FC1EFB57EF1DFB4E" box="[908,1099,1240,1264]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="Caribbean islands" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Caribbean islands</location>
(GBIF Secretariat 2021, 
<bibRefCitation author="POWO" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" refId="ref2996" refString="POWO (2021) Plants of the World. Royal Botanic Gardens Kew. Available from: https: // powo. science. kew. org / taxon / urn: lsid: ipni. org: names: 941331 - 1 (accessed 3 December 2021)." type="url" year="2021">POWO 2021</bibRefCitation>
, REFLORA 2022). 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FE01FB73E94DFAAA" box="[403,539,1276,1300]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="Interestingly" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Interestingly</location>
, there is some controversy on the origin of this plant. 
<bibRefCitation author="Scheen, A. - C. &amp; Albert, V. A." box="[1107,1360,1276,1300]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="173 - 181" refId="ref3457" refString="Scheen, A. - C. &amp; Albert, V. A. (2009) Molecular phylogenetics of the Leucas group (Lamioideae; Lamiaceae). Systematic Botany 34: 173 - 181. https: // doi. org / 10.1600 / 036364409787602366" type="journal article" year="2009">Scheen &amp; Albert (2009)</bibRefCitation>
indicate an 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FF3AFAAFEBAFFA86" box="[168,249,1312,1336]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="African" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">African</location>
origin, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Morales, R." box="[377,543,1312,1336]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="199 - 223" refId="ref2719" refString="Morales, R. (2011) Las labiadas (Lamiaceae) de Guinea Ecuatorial. Anales del Jardin Botanico de Madrid 68: 199 - 223. https: // doi. org / 10.3989 / ajbm. 2288" type="journal article" year="2011">Morales (2011)</bibRefCitation>
states that it probably comes from America. However, an 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FB05FAAFEFBEFA86" box="[1175,1256,1312,1336]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="African" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">African</location>
or at least an 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FA11FAAFEB9CFAE2" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="Old World" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Old World</location>
origin is much more plausible considering the center of species richness of the genus, the distribution of close relatives and related genera. 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FEF1FAE7EADAFA3E" box="[355,396,1384,1408]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="The" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">The</location>
species probably arrived in the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FD64FAE7E832FA3E" box="[758,868,1384,1408]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="Caribbean" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Caribbean</location>
relatively early during the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03CC87AA2F26FFE1FF2FF890EADDFF65:8EBA60672F24FFE0FB05FAE7EFABFAC1" box="[1175,1277,1384,1407]" country="Australia" county="South America" municipality="Lesser Antilles" name="European" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">European</location>
colonization as the epithet refers to the island of 
<collectingCountry box="[497,616,1420,1444]" name="Martinique" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Martinique</collectingCountry>
in the 
<collectingMunicipality box="[692,855,1420,1444]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Lesser Antilles</collectingMunicipality>
, and the 
<typeStatus box="[954,1000,1420,1444]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">type</typeStatus>
specimen may have been collected there. The distribution of the species in America has remained restricted to the Caribbean and 
<collectingCounty box="[1091,1252,1456,1480]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">South America</collectingCounty>
(GBIF Secretariat 2021).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,1204,2092]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">
We do not know how the species arrived in 
<collectingCountry box="[650,735,1528,1552]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. It is not particularly attractive, but it is intensely aromatic and used as a medicinal tea in Africa, 
<collectingCountry box="[435,501,1564,1588]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[511,568,1564,1588]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">India</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[622,687,1564,1588]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Li, H. - W. &amp; Hedge, I. C." box="[701,889,1564,1588]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="50 - 299" refId="ref2545" refString="Li, H. - W. &amp; Hedge, I. C. (1994) Lamiaceae. In: Wu, C. Y. &amp; Raven, P. H. (eds.) Flora of China vol. 17. Science Press, Beijing &amp; Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis, pp. 50 - 299." type="book chapter" year="1994">Li &amp; Hedge 1994</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chouhan, H. S. &amp; Singh, S. K." box="[899,1150,1564,1588]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="13 - 26" refId="ref1893" refString="Chouhan, H. S. &amp; Singh, S. K. (2011) A review of plants of genus Leucas. Journal of Pharmacognosy and Phytotherapy 3: 13 - 26." type="journal article" year="2011">Chouhan &amp; Singh 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gomes de Melo, J. &amp; Gaspar-Santos, A. &amp; Cavalcanti de Amorim, E. L. &amp; Carneiro do Nascimento, S &amp; Paulino de Albuquerque, U." box="[1160,1447,1564,1588]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="365359" refId="ref2149" refString="Gomes de Melo, J., Gaspar-Santos, A., Cavalcanti de Amorim, E. L., Carneiro do Nascimento, S &amp; Paulino de Albuquerque, U. (2011) Medicinal plants used as antitumor agents in Brazil: an ethnobotanical approach. Evidence-Based Complementary and Alternative Medicine 2011: 365359. https: // doi. org / 10.1155 / 2011 / 365359" type="journal article" year="2011">
Gomes de Melo 
<emphasis box="[1334,1387,1564,1588]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ugwah-Oguejiofor, C. J. &amp; Eze, U. A. &amp; Bello, S. O. &amp; Etuk, E. U. &amp; Ameh, G. I. &amp; Ugwah, O. M." box="[136,464,1600,1624]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="87 - 91" refId="ref3554" refString="Ugwah-Oguejiofor, C. J., Eze, U. A., Bello, S. O., Etuk, E. U., Ameh, G. I. &amp; Ugwah, O. M. (2015) Anticonvulsant and sedative activities of aqueous leave extract of Leucas martinicensis (Jacq.) R. Br. Nigerian Journal of Basic and Applied Science 23: 87 - 91. https: // doi. org / 10.4314 / njbas. v 23 i 2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Ugwah-Oguejiofor 
<emphasis box="[346,400,1600,1624]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
); as habitually observed in many plants of 
<taxonomicName box="[920,1035,1600,1624]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Lamiaceae</taxonomicName>
family (
<emphasis box="[1128,1166,1601,1624]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">e.g.</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Heinrich, M." box="[1179,1336,1600,1624]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="475 - 488" refId="ref2425" refString="Heinrich, M. (1992) Economic botany of American Labiatae. In: Harley, R. M. &amp; Reynolds, T. (eds.) Advances in Labiatae science. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, pp. 475 - 488." type="book chapter" year="1992">Heinrich 1992</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lawrence, B. M." pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="399 - 436" refId="ref2493" refString="Lawrence, B. M. (1992) Chemical components of Labiatae oils and their exploitation. In: Harley, R. M. &amp; Reynolds, T. (eds.) Advances in Labiatae science. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, pp. 399 - 436." type="book chapter" year="1992">Lawrence 1992</bibRefCitation>
, Rivera-Nuñez &amp; Obón de Castro 1992, 
<bibRefCitation author="Perrino, E. V. &amp; Valerio, F. &amp; Jallali, S. &amp; Trani, A. &amp; Mezzapesa, G. N." box="[645,855,1636,1660]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="1952" refId="ref2887" refString="Perrino, E. V., Valerio, F., Jallali, S., Trani, A. &amp; Mezzapesa, G. N. (2021) Ecological and biological properties of Satureja cuneifolia Ten. and Thymus spinulosus Ten.: two wild officinal species of conservation concern in Apulia (Italy). A Preliminary Survey. Plants 10: 1952. https: // doi. org / 10.3390 / plants 10091952" type="journal article" year="2021">
Perrino 
<emphasis box="[733,789,1636,1660]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
2021
</bibRefCitation>
); also, it is burned as an insect repellent (
<bibRefCitation author="Li, H. - W. &amp; Hedge, I. C." pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="50 - 299" refId="ref2545" refString="Li, H. - W. &amp; Hedge, I. C. (1994) Lamiaceae. In: Wu, C. Y. &amp; Raven, P. H. (eds.) Flora of China vol. 17. Science Press, Beijing &amp; Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis, pp. 50 - 299." type="book chapter" year="1994">Li &amp; Hedge 1994</bibRefCitation>
). Its main aromatic component is Germacrene-D, a known insecticide (
<bibRefCitation author="Muhayimana, A. &amp; Chalchat, J. - C. &amp; Garry, R. - P." box="[964,1233,1672,1696]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="251 - 259" refId="ref2759" refString="Muhayimana, A., Chalchat, J. - C. &amp; Garry, R. - P. (1998) Chemical composition of essential oils of some medicinal plants from Rwanda. Journal of Essential Oil Research 10: 251 - 259." type="journal article" year="1998">
Muhayimana 
<emphasis box="[1114,1169,1672,1696]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
1998
</bibRefCitation>
, Ravi-Kiran &amp; SitaDevi 2007, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rattray, R. D. &amp; Van Wyk, B. E." box="[261,535,1708,1732]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="3712" refId="ref3083" refString="Rattray, R. D. &amp; Van Wyk, B. E. (2021) The botanical, chemical and ethnobotanical diversity of Southern African Lamiaceae. Molecules (Basel) 26: 3712. https: // doi. org / 10.3390 / molecules 26123712" type="journal article" year="2021">Rattray &amp; Van Wyk 2021</bibRefCitation>
). Antioxidant properties have been reported (
<bibRefCitation author="Rattray, R. D. &amp; Van Wyk, B. E." box="[1014,1296,1708,1732]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="3712" refId="ref3083" refString="Rattray, R. D. &amp; Van Wyk, B. E. (2021) The botanical, chemical and ethnobotanical diversity of Southern African Lamiaceae. Molecules (Basel) 26: 3712. https: // doi. org / 10.3390 / molecules 26123712" type="journal article" year="2021">Rattray &amp; Van Wyk, 2021</bibRefCitation>
). Also, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="1810" baseAuthorityName="Jacquin" baseAuthorityYear="1760" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Leucas" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="martinicensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Leucas martinicensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is used as an anticonvulsive and sedative (
<bibRefCitation author="Ugwah-Oguejiofor, C. J. &amp; Eze, U. A. &amp; Bello, S. O. &amp; Etuk, E. U. &amp; Ameh, G. I. &amp; Ugwah, O. M." box="[732,1061,1744,1768]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="87 - 91" refId="ref3554" refString="Ugwah-Oguejiofor, C. J., Eze, U. A., Bello, S. O., Etuk, E. U., Ameh, G. I. &amp; Ugwah, O. M. (2015) Anticonvulsant and sedative activities of aqueous leave extract of Leucas martinicensis (Jacq.) R. Br. Nigerian Journal of Basic and Applied Science 23: 87 - 91. https: // doi. org / 10.4314 / njbas. v 23 i 2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Ugwah-Oguejiofor 
<emphasis box="[943,997,1744,1768]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). These characteristics may facilitate intentional dispersal by humans, but the almost simultaneous appearance in widely separate places suggest unintentional introduction with commercial products.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,1204,2092]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">
In Africa, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="1810" baseAuthorityName="Jacquin" baseAuthorityYear="1760" box="[302,530,1853,1876]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Leucas" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="martinicensis">
<emphasis box="[302,530,1853,1876]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Leucas martinicensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a widespread ruderal and segetal weed (
<bibRefCitation author="Weber, G. &amp; Elemo, K. &amp; Lagoke, S. T. O." box="[1001,1200,1852,1876]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="167 - 178" refId="ref3693" refString="Weber, G., Elemo, K. &amp; Lagoke, S. T. O. (1995) Weed communities in intensified cereal-based cropping systems of the northern Guinea savanna. Weed Research 35: 167 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3180.1995. tb 02030. x" type="journal article" year="1995">
Weber 
<emphasis box="[1081,1136,1852,1876]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
1995
</bibRefCitation>
, Sheen &amp; Albert 2009, 
<bibRefCitation author="Azanaw, A. &amp; Ebabuye, Y. &amp; Abeje, Y." box="[136,355,1888,1912]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="53 - 62" refId="ref1714" refString="Azanaw, A., Ebabuye, Y. &amp; Abeje, Y. (2020) Qualitative and quantitative assessment of common weed species in West Gondar sesame growing area, Ethiopia. Journal of Advanced Research 9: 53 - 62. https: // doi. org / 10.18034 / abcjar. v 9 i 2.507" type="journal article" year="2020">
Azanaw 
<emphasis box="[232,289,1888,1912]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
); elsewhere, it is reported from ruderal and/or disturbed vegetation. The conditions of the habitat of the three populations in 
<collectingCountry box="[403,484,1924,1948]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Mexico</collectingCountry>
are consistent with these reports from the literature as described above. It will probably not invade more natural habitats but may cause problems for agricultural activities in the future, and specific eradication measures should be verified. The documentation of this new resident of the Mexican flora will facilitate tracking its future behavior.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
